To visualize word2vec learned vectors using plotly and tsne¶

  1. Find word clusters using word2vec

  2. Observe patterns in clustering

  3. Types of Analysis: (Analyize similarities to word "cold" and see how well its clustering the words)

    1. Simple word2vec trained with window size 5
    2. Word2vec trained with window size 3: To get rid of irregular similarites (Expected to remove irregularities in similarities: EX: israel - cold is similar) (Did not work as expected)
    3. Word2vec trained with hashtags removed in the corpus (Removed irregularities Israel not similar to cold anymore)

# preprocessing
import preprocessor as p
p.set_options(p.OPT.URL, p.OPT.EMOJI, p.OPT.SMILEY, p.OPT.MENTION, p.OPT.RESERVED, p.OPT.NUMBER)

#from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
# using nltk tokenize : will even split the hashtags and their words
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))


import re
import string

punctuations = '!"$%&\'()*+,-./:;<=>?@[\\]^_`{|}~'        # '#' not included to save the space.
regex = re.compile('[%s]' % re.escape(punctuations))
regexb=re.compile('b[\'\"]')


clean = []
                 
for tweet in data["text"].values:
    
    
    # clean tweet noise using tweet preprocessor
    tweet = p.clean(tweet)
     
    # convert unicode to str to use str functions
    tweet = str(tweet)
    
    tweet = regex.sub('', tweet)
    # lower casing
    tokens = map( str.lower , tweet.split())
            
    #remove punctuation
    #tokens =  map(lambda token:regex.sub('', token), tokens)  
    tokens = map(lambda token: token.strip(), tokens)
            
    #filter empty strings
    tokens = filter(lambda token: token != '' and token!=' ', tokens )  
   
            
    # remove stopwords
    tokens = filter(lambda word: word not in stop_words, tokens)
    if '.' in tweet:
        print tweet
        break
    clean.append(tokens)
In [3]:
# create wordvectors
import gensim
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
 
model = gensim.models.Word2Vec(sg=0, sentences= clean, size=100, window=5)
w2v = dict(zip(model.wv.index2word, model.wv.syn0))


# create list of words and respective vectors

vectors= []
labels = []
for word, vector in w2v.iteritems():
    
    vectors.append(vector)
    labels.append(word)

tsne = TSNE(n_components=2)

# transform the generated word2vec vectors
X_tsne = tsne.fit_transform(vectors)

N = len(vectors)
random_x = X_tsne[:, 0]
random_y = X_tsne[:, 1]

"cold" too has caputred all the required words such as recordshattering. Some interesting irregularites:¶

  1. I wonder why florida is here on the top? its valid this was tweet abt florida in the data:

    "(Reuters) - A rare winter storm hit the U.S. Southeast on Wednesday, bringing Florida's capital its first snow in three decades"

  2. Why is Israel vecotor closer with cold ?

    a. The reason is simple, these two are not related to cold. But some of israili channels reported the news and have, included #israel in the tweet for their publicity. It is just that.

    b. In some cases, the tweets include daily news summary of all the headlines. In which case you can expect different news , to be in the same sentence. But word2vec will fail ove such a dataset.

    c. EX: #israel #ynet #news broadcast by #emetnewspress s korea offers to talk with north on olympics cooperation,2018-01-02 06

WorkAround/Solution¶

  1. One work around is we reduce the window size of the word2vec training algorithm from five to three.

  2. We can also try removing the hashtags which seem to create the noise.

# preprocessing
import preprocessor as p
p.set_options(p.OPT.URL, p.OPT.EMOJI, p.OPT.SMILEY, p.OPT.MENTION, p.OPT.RESERVED, p.OPT.NUMBER, p.OPT.HASHTAG)

#from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
# using nltk tokenize : will even split the hashtags and their words
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))


import re
import string

punctuations = '!"$%&\'()*+,-./:;<=>?@[\\]^_`{|}~'        # '#' not included to save the space.
regex = re.compile('[%s]' % re.escape(punctuations))
regexb=re.compile('b[\'\"]')


clean = []
                 
for tweet in data["text"].values:
    
    
    # clean tweet noise using tweet preprocessor
    tweet = p.clean(tweet)
     
    # convert unicode to str to use str functions
    tweet = str(tweet)
    
    tweet = regex.sub('', tweet)
    # lower casing
    tokens = map( str.lower , tweet.split())
            
    #remove punctuation
    #tokens =  map(lambda token:regex.sub('', token), tokens)  
    tokens = map(lambda token: token.strip(), tokens)
            
    #filter empty strings
    tokens = filter(lambda token: token != '' and token!=' ', tokens )  
   
            
    # remove stopwords
    tokens = filter(lambda word: word not in stop_words, tokens)
    if '.' in tweet:
        print tweet
        break
    clean.append(tokens)

    
    
    



# create wordvectors
import gensim
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
 
model = gensim.models.Word2Vec(sg=0, sentences= clean, size=300, window=2)
w2v = dict(zip(model.wv.index2word, model.wv.syn0))


# create list of words and respective vectors

vectors= []
labels = []
for word, vector in w2v.iteritems():
    
    vectors.append(vector)
    labels.append(word)

Conclusion:¶

As you can clearly word2vec works better / clusters the words better when the hashtags are remvoed.

It seems like for clustering related words, hashtags are noise for the task. It may have other uses though

And reducing the window size, didnt help remove the noise in the similiarties.
